Constraint-First Math

A symbol-light system for solving without standard arithmetic/algebra/geometry

I’ll call it:

CFM-1: Constraint-First Math

A pre-symbolic math layer where problems are represented as:
	•	states
	•	constraints
	•	moves
	•	stability checks

Instead of “equation solving,” it does valid-state finding.

⸻

1. Core primitives

A. Thing

Any object, idea, state, token, event, or candidate.

Written as:
[x]

Examples:
	•	[door]
	•	[path-a]
	•	[answer-3]

This is just identity, not number.

⸻

B. Link

A relation between things.

Written as:
[x] ~ [y]

Meaning:
	•	connected to
	•	affects
	•	comparable to
	•	transforms into

The exact meaning is context-bound.

⸻

C. Gate

A constraint filter.

Written as:
[x] |> rule

Read as:
“x passes through rule”

If valid, it survives.
If not, it gets rejected.

Example:
[candidate] |> allowed

This is your “such that” upgrade in operational form.

⸻

D. Move

A transformation.

Written as:
[x] -> [y]

Meaning:
x can become y
or
state transition from x to y

⸻

E. Field

A possibility space.

Written as:
{ ... }

Example:
{ [a], [b], [c] }

This is not necessarily a numeric set in the usual sense. More like a search pool.

⸻

F. Lock

A stable solution state.

Written as:
[x] !!

Meaning:
x is selected / stabilized / accepted

⸻

2. Problem format

Every problem becomes:

Field

What can exist?

Rules

What must be true?

Moves

How can states change?

Lock condition

When do we stop?

So:

Problem = Field + Gates + Moves + Lock

That’s the whole engine.

⸻

3. Example problem solved without normal math

Problem

You have three boxes. One contains gold.
Only one label is true.

Labels:
	•	Box A says: “Gold is in B”
	•	Box B says: “Gold is not in B”
	•	Box C says: “Gold is in C”

Find the gold.

⸻

CFM-1 representation

Field

{ [gold-in-A], [gold-in-B], [gold-in-C] }

Gates

Each candidate must pass:
	•	|> exactly-one-true

Evaluate candidate 1

[gold-in-A] |> exactly-one-true

Check statements:
	•	A says B → false
	•	B says not B → true
	•	C says C → false

One true.

So:
[gold-in-A] !!

Actually wait—that means the gold is in A, not B.
That’s why this system is useful: the gate reveals the stable state without needing algebra.

⸻

4. Maze solving without geometry

Problem

Find a way out.

Field

All reachable states:
{ [start], [path-1], [path-2], [dead-end], [exit] }

Links

[start] ~ [path-1]
[start] ~ [path-2]
[path-1] ~ [dead-end]
[path-2] ~ [exit]

Rule

|> reaches-exit

Move policy

Explore links until a state passes the gate.

Result

[path-2] !!

No coordinates. No distances. No geometry symbols.
Just connectivity and survival.

⸻

5. What arithmetic/algebra/geometry become in this system

They don’t disappear. They get compiled downward.

Arithmetic becomes:
	•	accumulation
	•	repetition
	•	comparison of traces

Instead of 3 + 2 = 5, you can represent:
	•	a state gains two more tokens
	•	resulting state has merged inventory

Like:
[stack-3] +gain [token] +gain [token] -> [stack-5]

But even that can be more primitive:
[state] -> [more-state]

⸻

Algebra becomes:
	•	placeholder manipulation
	•	rule-preserving substitution
	•	constraint propagation

Instead of:
x + 2 = 5

You say:
	•	[x] is unknown
	•	when merged with [2], it must pass gate [matches-5]

So:
[x] +with [2] |> matches-[5]

Then test candidates or infer compatible states.

⸻

Geometry becomes:
	•	adjacency
	•	enclosure
	•	continuity
	•	transformation under movement

So a triangle is no longer “three-sided shape in Euclidean space”
but:
	•	three nodes
	•	mutually linked boundary
	•	enclosed stable loop

That is geometry stripped to topology/constraint.

⸻

6. This fits your “such that” idea directly

Standard math says:

\{x \mid P(x)\}

CFM-1 says:

{ [x] } |> P

or more usefully:

Field |> Gate -> Survivors

That’s stronger operationally.

Because instead of merely describing a subset, it describes:
	•	the source space
	•	the filter
	•	the surviving candidates

So your “such that” intuition was pointing at a real upgrade:

from static description
to executable selection

